\begin{definition}
Given two functions $f,g$, there exists a product, called \emph{integral Moyal's product} $f\star g$ defined so that (\ref{eq236:ps}) holds. It is given by
\begin{equation}\label{eq35:ps}
	(f\star g)(Z)=2^{2n}\int d\mu(X) d\mu(Y) f(X)g(Y) \exp\Big[\frac{2i}{\vartheta}(Z\Lambda Y+Y\Lambda X+ X\Lambda Z)\Big]
\end{equation}
where $X=(p,q)$ and $\Lambda$ is the Poisson structure.
\
